{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015bkxAnw1nVndKZZLpkVEj8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me analyze each behavior carefully using the framework provided.\n\n**Behavior 1: The generated reply references specific points from the incoming email rather than producing a generic response.**\n\n- MOCK-MISS: This is about whether the LLM actually uses the email content to produce a context-aware response, not just generic text. This is fundamentally about LLM output quality.\n- REAL-INFRA: No real OS/network needed.\n- LLM-DEP: Yes. This is about whether the LLM references specific points - that's exactly what an LLM decides. A mock LLM returning a constant would always \"pass\" because you'd just make the mock return something with references. \n\nThe real failure mode here is whether the actual LLM produces generic versus contextual responses, which means this falls into the **Agentic** level—you can't stub this out because a deterministic assertion would just trap you into validating the mock's behavior rather than the real LLM's judgment.\n\n**Behavior 2: The factual consistency check flags claims in the draft that contradict entries in the knowledge base.**\n\nThis depends on whether the consistency checker is LLM-based or deterministic. If it's using an LLM to make judgment calls about what contradicts the knowledge base, that's LLM-dependent and requires real evaluation. If it's a rule-based algorithm, it could be tested at the Integration level, but the system description suggests it's making semantic judgments about consistency, which points toward needing actual LLM reasoning.\n\n**Behavior 3: When the knowledge base has no relevant entries, the draft includes a disclaimer rather than fabricating facts.**\n\nThis is testing whether the LLM actually adds a disclaimer or makes things up when the KB is empty—that's pure LLM behavior that can't be reliably mocked, so it requires **Agentic** level testing to verify the real model's response. So the key distinction is whether the disclaimer comes from the code itself or from the LLM's own judgment. If the system just injects a disclaimer string when KB is empty, that's deterministic and testable at the Integration level. But the behavior description suggests the LLM is choosing not to fabricate and including a disclaimer instead—that's an LLM decision, making it Agentic. The phrasing \"rather than fabricating facts\" is the tell here, since it's about what the LLM actually does versus what it could do wrong.\n\nNow looking at the approval workflow behavior—this is about control flow and whether the system prevents automatic sending without explicit user approval. wait for approval? No real network needed—I can mock the email sending and test the workflow state machine in integration. This isn't about LLM output quality, just deterministic control logic: does the system actually check for approval before sending? That's testable by verifying the send function isn't called prematurely. The minimum level is integration since the approval state needs to wire to the send action across modules, and I don't need real OS/network or AI/ML components for this.\n\nFor the full end-to-end sequence with a real email thread—reading, generating a draft, checking facts, then presenting for approval—that's explicitly multiple agentic steps involving LLM calls in sequence. This pushes it to workflow level since the entire pipeline needs to work together with real email data.\n\nNow I'm assigning probability levels to each behavior based on these assessments. For the disclaimer behavior, the logic hinges on whether the LLM decides to include a disclaimer or risk fabrication. The approval workflow is primarily an integration concern since it requires multiple modules working together, with minimal agentic involvement. The end-to-end sequence test is mostly about orchestration rather than testing any single capability deeply.\n\nWorkflow testing dominates the final behavior since it's fundamentally about validating the entire pipeline execution.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9527,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9527},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8dc3e60c-3bf0-4f1b-93d2-233950ef34f7","uuid":"8026af04-9114-4f59-a8b2-4bc0e1a548f7"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015bkxAnw1nVndKZZLpkVEj8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01DXEhknmkDBi6rjZ28Tr6Tn","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The generated reply references specific points from the incoming email rather than producing a generic response.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: Whether the generated reply is contextual vs. generic is entirely a function of the real LLM's behavior. A stub replacement would return a constant string, meaning the test would always pass regardless of whether the real model actually attends to email content. MOCK-HIDE: Mocking the LLM with a pre-written reply that includes references would definitionally pass, hiding any real failure in the model's behavior. REJECTION-GATE: No behavior text disqualifies Agentic — there is no purely deterministic algorithmic path that verifies contextual referencing; it is the LLM's output quality itself being tested. Deterministic-assertion trap applies: even if the assertion checked for a specific quoted phrase, a stub returning that phrase would trivially pass without exercising real model behavior.","test_description":"Supply a real multi-turn email thread containing several specific, named facts (e.g., a meeting time, a named product, a quoted figure). Invoke the full draft-generation step with a real LLM. Assert that the draft contains at least one direct reference to a named fact from the thread and does not read as a boilerplate reply that would fit any email. Run multiple times to confirm consistency.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.85,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The factual consistency check flags claims in the draft that contradict entries in the knowledge base.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: Deciding whether a claim 'contradicts' a KB entry is a semantic judgment — exactly the kind of decision that varies with the real model's behavior. A deterministic stub could be scripted to always return 'contradiction found', but that proves nothing about whether the real checker correctly identifies semantic contradictions. MOCK-HIDE: Any stub for the consistency-checker component would be programmed to return the expected flag, hiding real failures in the model's ability to recognize contradictions. REJECTION-GATE: The behavior text says the system 'checks the draft for factual consistency' — there is no claim that this is a deterministic keyword or exact-match algorithm that could be isolated to Integration. The failure mode is the model failing to detect a real semantic contradiction, which requires the real model.","test_description":"Seed the knowledge base with an entry stating a specific fact (e.g., 'Product X costs $500'). Craft or generate a draft that asserts a contradictory claim ('Product X costs $200'). Run the real consistency checker and assert it returns a flag identifying the contradicted claim. Also test a non-contradicting draft to confirm no false positives.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.83,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the knowledge base has no relevant entries, the draft includes a disclaimer rather than fabricating facts.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"LLM-DEP: The phrase 'rather than fabricating facts' reveals the failure mode: the real LLM might invent plausible-sounding but false content when KB is empty. Whether the model actually includes a disclaimer vs. hallucinating is a real-model quality question. If a programmatic code path simply appended a disclaimer string, 'rather than fabricating' would be vacuous — the behavior description implies the LLM itself must choose the disclaimer path. MOCK-HIDE: A stub returning a disclaimer-containing response would always pass, hiding real hallucination failures. REJECTION-GATE: No behavior text says the disclaimer is injected by deterministic post-processing code independent of the LLM. Until that design is confirmed, Agentic is required.","test_description":"Configure the KB to return empty results for any query. Provide a topic that the LLM could plausibly hallucinate about. Invoke real draft generation. Assert the draft contains a disclaimer phrase (e.g., 'I don't have confirmed information') and does not contain confident factual claims about the topic. Run several times to reduce stochastic pass chance.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.73,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The approval workflow blocks sending until the user explicitly approves — no draft is sent automatically.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure mode — sending without approval — only appears when the approval-state module is wired to the send-trigger module. A unit test of the approval check function alone cannot verify that the send action actually reads that state before firing. REAL-INFRA: Real email sending infrastructure is not needed; a mock send client suffices to observe whether send() is called prematurely. LLM-DEP: This is purely control-flow logic with no dependence on LLM output quality. MULTI-STEP: No chained LLM steps required. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network needed — mock sender captures calls. (b) No AI/ML output dependency. (c) No chained agentic steps. Integration is sufficient.","test_description":"Wire the approval module to a mock email sender. Trigger the full post-generation flow (skip real LLM with a stub draft). Assert the mock sender's send() method is never called before the approval signal is issued. Then issue approval and assert send() is called exactly once. Also test that a second approval call does not re-send.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.15,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The full sequence — read thread, generate draft, check facts, present for approval — works end-to-end for a real email thread.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"MULTI-STEP: The sequence explicitly chains at least two real agentic steps: (1) LLM draft generation and (2) LLM/AI factual consistency check, plus orchestration steps for reading and approval presentation. Failures can emerge from state handed between steps — e.g., the draft passed to the checker is truncated, or the approval gate receives the wrong draft version — which only appear when all steps run in sequence with real models. LLM-DEP: Both generation and consistency checking depend on real model outputs, meaning a stub pipeline would not surface real inter-step failures. REJECTION-GATE: No behavior text limits this to a single agentic step or a deterministic pipeline — 'full sequence' and 'real email thread' explicitly require the complete multi-step agent pipeline.","test_description":"Provide a real incoming email thread. Run the complete pipeline with real LLM calls for both generation and consistency checking, and a real (or realistic fixture-backed) KB. Assert: the draft is non-empty and references thread content; the consistency result is produced and attached to the draft; the approval gate is reached and no send occurs until approval; after approval the send step fires. Treat any step failure or unexpected ordering as a test failure.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.15,"Workflow":0.75}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":9527,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":9527},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8dc3e60c-3bf0-4f1b-93d2-233950ef34f7","uuid":"3f1a024f-743d-4ecd-bedb-24ea1d13f767"}
